70
00:03:21,715 --> 00:03:25,497
26063, resolution to update the ordinance establishing the Medford Commission for Persons with Disabilities.

71
00:03:26,218 --> 00:03:38,744
Whereas, the Medford Commission for Persons with Disabilities approved a proposed ordinance change that would remove exclusionary language concerning drug use, modernize terminology throughout the language of the ordinance, and clarify and positively define the commission's role.

72
00:03:39,144 --> 00:03:45,268
Now therefore, be it resolved by the Medford City Council that we update the ordinance establishing the commission for persons with disabilities.

73
00:03:45,388 --> 00:03:45,968
Councillor Lemming.

74
00:03:46,719 --> 00:03:48,540
Thank you, Council President Behrs.

75
00:03:49,361 --> 00:04:03,392
So the Medford Commission for Persons with Disabilities has been very hard at work coming up with and agreeing on new language for their proposed ordinance.

76
00:04:03,572 --> 00:04:04,593
I don't want to take

77
00:04:05,213 --> 00:04:06,734
Any credit away from them.

78
00:04:06,794 --> 00:04:19,523
I'm simply presenting the work that they have all spent a lot of time on and Want to obviously want to want to see this past

79
00:04:21,684 --> 00:04:31,149
A letter from the Commission is included in the agenda packet, essentially summarizing what the changes are.

80
00:04:31,590 --> 00:04:42,376
We also have an updated draft of the new ordinance establishing the Medford Commissions for Persons with Disabilities.

81
00:04:43,176 --> 00:05:04,756
The three essential changes here are removal of exclusionary languages, language concerning drug use, modernizing terminology, so the current ordinance contains words such as handicap, which has been widely abandoned in favor of disability or persons with disabilities.

82
00:05:05,978 --> 00:05:10,301
and clarifying and positively defining the commission's role.

83
00:05:11,402 --> 00:05:20,450
The mayor is already aware of these changes and is reviewing the ordinance herself.

84
00:05:21,231 --> 00:05:32,020
My only recommendation at this stage would just be for a formal request for legal review, but otherwise everything seems in order and I would like to give

85
00:05:32,560 --> 00:05:44,703
time for the members of the commission to speak and just talk about some of their own work on this and some of the background behind it.

86
00:05:44,843 --> 00:05:53,366
And I see that a couple of them are joining us on Zoom and I believe some folks are in the chamber as well.

87
00:05:55,066 --> 00:05:56,587
And that is what I got.

88
00:05:57,927 --> 00:06:00,068
So I just would love to hear them talk about this.

89
00:06:00,228 --> 00:06:06,909
We have folks here from the commission and from our Office of Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion, both in the chambers and on Zoom.

90
00:06:07,829 --> 00:06:11,330
We do have two, seems like two comments from counselors before we go.

91
00:06:11,390 --> 00:06:17,932
So I'll go to Vice President Lazaro and Counselor Tseng, and then we will hear from our commissioners and our DEI office team.

92
00:06:18,672 --> 00:06:19,712
Counselor Lazaro.

93
00:06:21,426 --> 00:06:31,892
Thank you Councillor Lemming for bringing this forward and to the commission and our DEI officer and director and office generally.

94
00:06:32,333 --> 00:06:50,063
I really appreciate especially it happens to be something that I have an interest in as the suggested change from the phrasing currently engaging in the illegal use of drugs and removing that from the

95
00:06:52,074 --> 00:07:00,998
from the phrasing and the legal language is great because it's not necessary and stigmatizing.

96
00:07:01,038 --> 00:07:07,121
And I think there's a lot of ways we can scrub things from our local laws and our state laws.

97
00:07:07,161 --> 00:07:19,087
They just made a big change at the state level to this effect and the Department of Developmental Services

98
00:07:19,627 --> 00:07:21,889
I can't remember what it's called, but they made a bunch of changes.

99
00:07:21,930 --> 00:07:26,754
They took out a bunch of words that were really derogatory, now have developed these derogatory meanings.

100
00:07:28,196 --> 00:07:37,446
Ultimately, of course, the hope for the world is that words don't have these meanings because you don't assign those meanings to the way people feel about each other.

101
00:07:37,466 --> 00:07:40,409
Then you stop having to change which words we use because

102
00:07:40,969 --> 00:07:43,872
everybody treats each other better and then we don't have to keep doing this.

103
00:07:43,952 --> 00:07:59,585
But in the meantime, we can start with taking out some of these words that have these connotations and we can start using words that people choose for themselves and be more open and equity minded and focused on

104
00:08:00,266 --> 00:08:03,670
person first language and lovely things like that.

105
00:08:03,910 --> 00:08:06,232
And I really appreciate the work that's gone into this.

106
00:08:06,653 --> 00:08:14,922
So I'm very much in favor and would motion to approve once we get to that point, but looking forward to hearing from the folks that have come tonight.

107
00:08:15,222 --> 00:08:15,742
So thank you.

108
00:08:17,905 --> 00:08:18,465
Thank you.

109
00:08:18,666 --> 00:08:19,667
Councilor Sang.

110
00:08:20,682 --> 00:08:21,062
Thank you.

111
00:08:21,442 --> 00:08:49,968
Like Councilor Lazaro, I'm very grateful to the members of the commission who have put their work, put so much work into updating the language to reflect what we actually know to be true of the situation, that we shouldn't be stigmatizing drug use or using words that are outdated, that don't reflect the actual experience of what it is to be disabled in our community, to use language, to get rid of outdated language that

112
00:08:50,949 --> 00:08:54,536
creates exclusion rather than inclusion in our community.

113
00:08:55,698 --> 00:09:02,712
And I am particularly inspired by the fact that this is grassroots-led, led by the members of the commission.

114
00:09:03,972 --> 00:09:10,994
My only question is that in section 11, the effective date at the very end, there seems to maybe be a typo.

115
00:09:12,394 --> 00:09:21,556
It says, this ordinance shall take effect upon passage by the city council in approval by the mayor in accordance with the, and the sentence seems to drop off there.

116
00:09:22,076 --> 00:09:32,919
So I'm just wondering if the last few words after mayor are just extraneous or whether there was something that was supposed to come after those words.

117
00:09:33,759 --> 00:09:34,120
Thank you.

118
00:09:36,422 --> 00:09:38,283
Thank you, Vice President Lazaro, Councilor Sang.

119
00:09:39,084 --> 00:09:44,869
We can hear from our commissioners and our wonderful staff team next.

120
00:09:45,049 --> 00:09:51,295
So if you want to come to the podium, I will get our microphone going for you.

121
00:09:51,355 --> 00:09:57,260
And if you are from the commission and planning to say something on Zoom, please raise your hand on Zoom.

122
00:10:06,390 --> 00:10:06,850
You're on.

123
00:10:08,091 --> 00:10:08,591
Good evening.

124
00:10:09,031 --> 00:10:09,431
Good evening.

125
00:10:10,231 --> 00:10:23,755
Anthony Antriadola, 75 Lawrence Road, Medford, Mass, Medford High School, class of 1978, and a newly appointed commissioner on the Persons with Disability Commission here in Medford.

126
00:10:23,855 --> 00:10:34,559
And I want to, first off, thank Councilor Lemming for coming out to our meeting and bringing this ordinance forward.

127
00:10:35,712 --> 00:10:50,738
You know, I think it's very important for the city to, you know, fix old language and ordinances that really don't reflect who we are now in Medford and what we want to be in the future, you know.

128
00:10:51,278 --> 00:10:56,820
The language in the old ordinance is something that I noticed when I was appointed to the commission.

129
00:10:56,840 --> 00:10:58,401
I wanted to know what I was getting into.

130
00:10:58,481 --> 00:11:04,143
And when I read it, I was very upset to see that, you know, how the language was used to kind

131
00:11:05,399 --> 00:11:23,950
minimize people in our community rather than kind of go to their strengths, what people with disabilities bring to Medford, not what somewhere in the old ordinance it says we will work to solve the problems of the people with disabilities.

132
00:11:26,456 --> 00:11:40,762
Our commission is here to help the city, to help the city remove barriers so people with disabilities can live, work, and thrive in Medford like everyone else.

133
00:11:42,688 --> 00:11:45,790
Our city is 12% disabled.

134
00:11:46,150 --> 00:11:50,212
It's a very large number of people living in our community that have a disability.

135
00:11:50,632 --> 00:12:02,898
And by age 65, that number rises dramatically when people have an impaired mobility somewhere within 30% to 40% of our population of people age 65 or older.

136
00:12:02,938 --> 00:12:11,962
So it's a significant number of people in Medford with disabilities that need support and need to have

137
00:12:12,747 --> 00:12:18,588
a commission that could actually represent them in ways that are significant.

138
00:12:20,068 --> 00:12:41,092
One of the main reasons I wanted to bring this forward is because there are a number of opportunities in the city where our commission can help, where, you know, especially in zoning and building, it's real important that, you know, things are done correctly the first time.

139
00:12:42,547 --> 00:13:03,342
it would be a lot more expensive to retrofit our city after, say, oh, you know, this particular building is not accessible or we could have made this ramp this way or maybe we should have asked the people who struggle with getting around Method Square what we're going to do in Method Square.

140
00:13:04,122 --> 00:13:10,667
Because, you know, right now I think people with disabilities are the major residents

141
00:13:11,746 --> 00:13:12,487
of Meffitt Square.

142
00:13:12,507 --> 00:13:17,091
I think there's more than 400 people living with disabilities right here in Meffitt Square.

143
00:13:17,131 --> 00:13:19,453
So they're a majority of the population.

144
00:13:19,793 --> 00:13:35,587
So when we look at things like Meffitt Square, it's real important that our commission can be involved and help in the process, help the council, help the administration, the mayor's office, or the DPW.

145
00:13:35,707 --> 00:13:37,809
We've worked with the Traffic Commission recently

146
00:13:39,099 --> 00:13:40,601
to try to do something about this.

147
00:13:40,621 --> 00:13:46,107
Our major crosswalk in Medford Square is not accessible.

148
00:13:46,548 --> 00:13:48,810
It hasn't been for maybe 30 years.

149
00:13:48,830 --> 00:13:57,701
30 years, there's a crosswalk that a person with a disability cannot make it safely to the other side.

150
00:13:58,433 --> 00:14:03,294
And our commission went out and worked with the traffic commission to time the light.

151
00:14:03,734 --> 00:14:05,174
And it's not safe.

152
00:14:06,135 --> 00:14:09,895
And these are the kinds of things that we want to focus on.

153
00:14:10,475 --> 00:14:14,756
And we want to just update this ordinance and to let you all know that we're here.

154
00:14:15,316 --> 00:14:21,118
We want to be part of the changes in Medford.

155
00:14:21,698 --> 00:14:28,079
And I think we have a lot of experienced commissioners and people who want to give their time and energy

156
00:14:28,560 --> 00:14:31,421
to make a better city.

157
00:14:33,182 --> 00:14:42,666
People 65, 40% have impaired mobility and you become 65 in the blink of an eye.

158
00:14:43,647 --> 00:14:49,109
This isn't for me or for us, it's for you guys, it's for the future.

159
00:14:50,630 --> 00:14:55,752
These changes that we're making in the city need to benefit a new,

160
00:14:57,149 --> 00:15:01,333
new generation of people that have needs.

161
00:15:01,493 --> 00:15:13,964
And I'll stop rambling at the mouth, but I just want to thank you for all considering the changes and to thank the other commissioners and everyone that's been kind of supportive of this process.

162
00:15:14,445 --> 00:15:14,825
Thank you.

163
00:15:15,886 --> 00:15:16,647
Thank you, Anthony.

164
00:15:18,020 --> 00:15:28,626
And I just wanted to thank you and John and Joseph and Cameron and Kate and Susan from the commission and Francis and Nick and their support from the Office of Diversity, Equity and Inclusion.

165
00:15:28,646 --> 00:15:36,351
If folks haven't had a chance to take a look, there's a fantastic letter about this ordinance update that you guys drafted as well.

166
00:15:36,431 --> 00:15:39,913
So that's available for the public to read on our website.

167
00:15:45,245 --> 00:15:50,778
Is there anyone else from our Office of Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion or from the Commission for Persons with Disabilities?

168
00:15:50,838 --> 00:15:51,700
Frances is coming back.

169
00:15:51,860 --> 00:15:52,401
All right, great.

170
00:16:05,962 --> 00:16:07,483
All right, Director Nwaje, how are you?

171
00:16:07,644 --> 00:16:08,685
I'm good, thank you.

172
00:16:08,765 --> 00:16:09,946
How are you all doing?

173
00:16:10,106 --> 00:16:12,008
Good, thank you for this.

174
00:16:12,028 --> 00:16:16,772
So, Nick was going to speak, but I think he's left me up here by myself.

175
00:16:17,312 --> 00:16:21,596
I want to say first and foremost, a huge thank you to the members for

176
00:16:22,537 --> 00:16:23,999
that are currently on the commission.

177
00:16:24,099 --> 00:16:28,745
I want everybody to know and understand that it's not always about the numbers.

178
00:16:29,746 --> 00:16:32,610
It's about the passion and the effort that people bring.

179
00:16:33,371 --> 00:16:35,894
The commission is supposed to have nine people.

180
00:16:36,395 --> 00:16:38,738
For a long time, we floated with three.

181
00:16:38,838 --> 00:16:39,980
We're now up to six.

182
00:16:40,620 --> 00:16:45,904
And this was really their work and their drive, their language.

183
00:16:46,124 --> 00:16:51,387
I just, you know, did the administrative piece, let's say.

184
00:16:51,947 --> 00:16:55,510
So I am, I'm truly, truly proud of that.

185
00:16:56,430 --> 00:17:00,673
Something that Commissioner Andrew Toller said is really important.

186
00:17:01,093 --> 00:17:08,098
The original ordinance does include the Commission for Persons with Disabilities in so much work that gets done.

187
00:17:08,839 --> 00:17:13,742
And more and more recently, people have started reaching out to the commission.

188
00:17:14,363 --> 00:17:18,526
And it is important because it allows us to be able to

189
00:17:19,306 --> 00:17:24,347
share the recommendations, which may not necessarily be well received.

190
00:17:24,427 --> 00:17:28,428
However, those recommendations are founded and guided by law.

191
00:17:28,908 --> 00:17:39,530
So we avoid the huge costly mistakes that we now have to go back to and, you know, fix, replace, or live with and act like we don't see.

192
00:17:40,591 --> 00:17:41,911
It is my hope that

193
00:17:42,811 --> 00:17:47,933
the different departments, city council, folks continue to reach out to the commission.

194
00:17:48,453 --> 00:18:02,960
It is my hope that of the 400 plus that do live around Medford Square and of the 100 visually impaired members of the Medford community that we will expand.

195
00:18:03,740 --> 00:18:18,947
And we will have people that bring all their unique skill sets, everything from whether you are a late adult amputee to being born with a physical disability or a cognitive disability.

196
00:18:19,467 --> 00:18:24,290
So I just want to say that I'm truly proud to work with all of the commissioners.

197
00:18:25,310 --> 00:18:35,593
and proud to work with Mr. Karinge over here, who unfortunately was the one that almost got ran over when we were timing the traffic signals.

198
00:18:36,714 --> 00:18:39,735
So this is why those things are important, right?

199
00:18:39,815 --> 00:18:43,016
We can use technology.

200
00:18:43,456 --> 00:18:45,897
However, you actually have to be out there.

201
00:18:46,938 --> 00:18:50,524
what a white cane user might require to cross the street.

202
00:18:50,964 --> 00:18:57,475
It's very different from what a person that is using a mobility device might need.

203
00:18:57,575 --> 00:18:59,498
So there I rest.

204
00:19:01,547 --> 00:19:02,648
Thank you, Frances.

205
00:19:03,088 --> 00:19:12,453
And Nick, first off, thanks for putting yourself, to be frank, at risk to help make the city a better place.

206
00:19:12,533 --> 00:19:13,814
It shouldn't have to be that way.

207
00:19:15,155 --> 00:19:16,835
But you do so much for our community.

208
00:19:16,896 --> 00:19:25,120
And just really, that's not a great story to have to hear, but it is a story that people experience every day in our city.

209
00:19:25,260 --> 00:19:28,242
And that's something we need to change.

210
00:19:28,382 --> 00:19:30,043
So just wanted to say that before you have the floor.

211
00:19:31,247 --> 00:19:37,115
And it's empowering, too, because I think it was four commissioners went out with the director of traffic and engineering.

212
00:19:37,415 --> 00:19:39,538
So it's actually on site.

213
00:19:40,379 --> 00:19:43,523
It's not done virtually or using technology.

214
00:19:43,583 --> 00:19:47,048
It's actually a physical exercise that they do.

215
00:20:02,150 --> 00:20:05,651
Good evening, everyone.

216
00:20:05,811 --> 00:20:08,031
My name is Nicholas Kadinga.

217
00:20:09,832 --> 00:20:12,992
I work with Ms.

218
00:20:13,032 --> 00:20:19,714
Frances as the disability specialist here in City Hall.

219
00:20:20,734 --> 00:20:29,636
And I don't really have much to add, but I just want to just reiterate

220
00:20:32,303 --> 00:20:33,544
what has already been said.

221
00:20:36,485 --> 00:20:47,310
Since I've been working here, I've had the express pleasure of working with this AmeriCorps commission.

222
00:20:48,090 --> 00:20:58,314
And truly, the work that they do is definitely something to be commended, to say the least.

223
00:21:01,545 --> 00:21:11,494
I think I have grown as a resident of Medford having worked with them.

224
00:21:14,197 --> 00:21:18,801
I've also been able to relate a lot more.

225
00:21:21,646 --> 00:21:29,872
with my own city because of working with them.

226
00:21:30,573 --> 00:21:49,987
And I think their work is extremely necessary for us to even continue as a city if we really care about those that live here.

227
00:21:52,047 --> 00:22:17,280
Not to mention the sheer fact that whether you are born with a disability or not, the fact that we are humans made of bone and skin can easily find us in the place of having a disability, even if temporary.

228
00:22:19,247 --> 00:22:23,229
at any given time in life.

229
00:22:24,930 --> 00:22:45,320
And so this AmeriCorps commission not only works for those that have been clearly born with a disability, but also whoever will happen upon life's chances for any reason.

230
00:22:50,407 --> 00:23:03,778
With that, I just want to give my support to the commission and my thanks to City Council for hearing us out.

231
00:23:03,798 --> 00:23:04,498
Thank you.

232
00:23:05,479 --> 00:23:06,039
Thank you, Nick.

233
00:23:08,041 --> 00:23:18,949
And I just want to add, you brought up a good point, which is the dangers on our streets and sidewalks and lack of access to our buildings.

234
00:23:19,822 --> 00:23:29,143
may be particularly serious for people with disabilities, but we are all people with bones and skin.

235
00:23:30,936 --> 00:23:34,418
whether it's motor vehicles or whatever else, those dangers are for all of us.

236
00:23:34,458 --> 00:23:42,344
And if we can make our intersections safer, certainly focusing on making them safe for people with disabilities in our community, it makes it safer for everyone.

237
00:23:42,364 --> 00:23:44,986
And I think that's an important thing to recognize too.

238
00:23:45,086 --> 00:23:49,489
So we so appreciate the work that you guys in your office do and that the commission does.

239
00:23:50,950 --> 00:23:55,853
And I know a couple of counselors want to say some more, so I'll go to Vice President Lazaro and then Councilor Scarpelli.

240
00:23:55,953 --> 00:23:56,694
Vice President Lazaro.

241
00:23:58,780 --> 00:23:59,200
Thank you.

242
00:23:59,260 --> 00:24:03,603
I just wanted to highlight something that Nick said that I thought was really important.

243
00:24:05,164 --> 00:24:14,411
Talking about crossing the street in Medford Square, something that we have talked about a lot in walking audits,

244
00:24:16,232 --> 00:24:24,213
Last winter, after Dan Dill and Arthur Weber were killed in crosswalks, they were not disabled.

245
00:24:24,834 --> 00:24:37,756
They were killed in crosswalks by cars, and now the places that they were hit by cars have been fixed, and they are now both ADA accessible.

246
00:24:38,396 --> 00:24:45,057
But we shouldn't need somebody to get hit by a car to have a crosswalk fixed and made to be ADA accessible.

247
00:24:46,808 --> 00:24:50,726
And that's, those are a couple of only, you know, a handful of.

248
00:24:51,443 --> 00:24:57,684
crosswalks in Medford that are actually up to the standards that are supposedly required for crosswalks.

249
00:24:57,905 --> 00:25:06,346
And it highlights how interconnected disability services are to every other service in a city.

250
00:25:07,567 --> 00:25:20,670
Traffic, maintenance of roads and sidewalks, and something else that Nick said that really made me think is like, anybody, there are disabilities that are very visible, there are disabilities that are very invisible.

251
00:25:21,792 --> 00:25:23,760
mental health, substance use disorder.

252
00:25:26,249 --> 00:25:32,514
chronic pain, chronic illness, lots of things that happen to people that we don't see.

253
00:25:33,095 --> 00:25:44,065
And then you temporarily break a leg and then you cannot walk down the street and you can't cross the street, you can't get off of a sidewalk because there are no curb cuts.

254
00:25:44,465 --> 00:25:52,192
Or you have an infant in a stroller and you realize how difficult it is to traverse the city because the sidewalks are very uneven, there aren't curb cuts.

255
00:25:54,793 --> 00:26:00,174
When we do walking audits, we talk a lot about like, it's so hard just to walk from one place to another in town.

256
00:26:00,954 --> 00:26:06,355
Imagine how hard it is if you're in a wheelchair, you have a mobility device, and it's like a lot of people don't have to imagine.

257
00:26:06,395 --> 00:26:07,656
They just don't walk places.

258
00:26:07,716 --> 00:26:09,476
Maybe they have to hire a car.

259
00:26:09,596 --> 00:26:10,756
It's an additional expense.

260
00:26:10,816 --> 00:26:11,996
Maybe they have to take the ride.

261
00:26:12,036 --> 00:26:16,197
Maybe they have to add in a ton of extra time every time they go anywhere.

262
00:26:17,917 --> 00:26:21,058
It's things that many, many people are not considering.

263
00:26:21,558 --> 00:26:29,343
that it is our obligation as people who are governing the city and leading the city to always be considering.

264
00:26:30,564 --> 00:26:36,208
I appreciate the commission for calling it to our attention, but it needs to be at the forefront of our mind all the time.

265
00:26:37,489 --> 00:26:46,595
And things that improve, things that make life more accessible and livable for people with disabilities make life easier for everybody.

266
00:26:48,176 --> 00:26:50,418
It is an improvement that lifts all ships.

267
00:26:51,603 --> 00:26:55,168
Um, so, uh, again, great appreciation.

268
00:26:55,188 --> 00:26:58,912
Um, much obliged, uh, all of us.

