522
00:45:36,488 --> 00:45:40,394
Communications from the Mayor, 26050 submitted by Mayor Brianna Longo Kern.

523
00:45:40,514 --> 00:45:43,879
Special legislation to remove police chief and deputy positions from civil service.

524
00:45:44,770 --> 00:46:03,730
February 19th, 2026, dear President Behrs and members of the City Council, I respectfully request and recommend that your honorable body vote to authorize the Mayor, on behalf of the City, to petition the Massachusetts General Court for special legislation, substantially in the form as set forth below, relating to the exemption of the positions of Police Chief and Deputy Police Chief from the Civil Service Law, General Laws Chapter 31.

525
00:46:04,679 --> 00:46:18,171
Provided, however, that the general court may make clerical or editorial changes of form only to the bill unless the mayor approves amendments to the bill before enactment by the general court, and provided further that the mayor is hereby authorized to approve amendments which shall be within the scope of the general public objectives of this petition.

526
00:46:18,732 --> 00:46:20,273
Special act would provide as follows.

527
00:46:20,833 --> 00:46:31,043
An act exempting the positions of police chief and deputy police chief in the city of Medford from the civil service law, being enacted by the Senate and House of Representatives and general court assembled and by the authority of the same as follows.

528
00:46:31,683 --> 00:46:37,647
Section 1, the positions of police chief and deputy police chief in the city of Medford shall be exempt from Chapter 31 of the general laws.

529
00:46:38,307 --> 00:46:44,771
Section 2, this act shall not impair the civil service status of a person holding a position described in Section 1 on the effective date of this act.

530
00:46:45,392 --> 00:46:47,793
Section 3, this act shall take effect upon passage.

531
00:46:50,195 --> 00:46:51,315
Thank you for your attention to this matter.

532
00:46:51,515 --> 00:46:53,557
Respectfully submitted, Brianna Lungo Kern, Mayor.

533
00:46:55,057 --> 00:46:55,758
Councillor Scarpelli.

534
00:46:56,665 --> 00:46:57,786
Uh, thank you, Mr President.

535
00:46:57,946 --> 00:47:06,890
And, um, after last week's meeting, I know we talked and we were waiting for a representative from the city to answer any of our questions.

536
00:47:07,290 --> 00:47:19,076
I received a phone call from, um, from Harold McGillivray, who's the president of the I believe the, um, leadership union at the police department.

537
00:47:19,116 --> 00:47:23,899
This is this was part of the negotiation that all parties agreed on.

538
00:47:25,092 --> 00:47:28,593
So all the unions do support this initiative.

539
00:47:29,213 --> 00:47:51,837
So I would ask my fellow colleagues to move forward with this motion and this resolution for the fact that this was the wishes and the understanding of all the men and women in our Method Police Department that use this for negotiations during their last contract completion.

540
00:47:53,413 --> 00:47:55,360
I hope you all join me with approving this.

541
00:47:55,520 --> 00:47:55,881
Thank you.

542
00:47:57,025 --> 00:47:58,449
Thank you, Councillor Scarpelli.

543
00:47:58,489 --> 00:47:59,472
Vice President Lazaro.

544
00:48:01,042 --> 00:48:03,843
I appreciate that context, Councillor Scarpelli.

545
00:48:04,883 --> 00:48:18,186
That is, I think, the sticking point for all of us, not to speak for the rest of the council, but the sticking point for many, many of the councillors last time was that we didn't, we couldn't ask any questions of the administration.

546
00:48:18,226 --> 00:48:20,346
We just kind of, it was kind of plopped there for us.

547
00:48:21,547 --> 00:48:22,847
So we weren't sure what it was.

548
00:48:24,323 --> 00:48:28,686
what the story was and who all was in favor of it and why.

549
00:48:29,507 --> 00:48:50,784
But I do believe that removing the chief from civil service and the two deputy chiefs potentially, potential deputy chiefs from civil service opens up the field to a wider group of candidates, allows different, all different

550
00:48:51,127 --> 00:49:03,121
qualified candidates to come and apply for the job and it's best practice and it's just it's just a good thing for the city and the department and all parties seem to be in favor of it.

551
00:49:03,262 --> 00:49:06,926
So I'm glad to know that and I would be happy to move forward with this.

552
00:49:07,266 --> 00:49:07,587
Thank you.

553
00:49:08,187 --> 00:49:09,169
Thank you Councilor Zaro.

554
00:49:09,309 --> 00:49:10,871
We do have our chief and.

555
00:49:11,813 --> 00:49:13,915
Here, I don't know if Chief Buckley, you want to?

556
00:49:14,576 --> 00:49:18,119
I have a question, which is just generally, how did we arrive here?

557
00:49:19,080 --> 00:49:21,862
Why was it important that this happened through collective bargaining?

558
00:49:21,882 --> 00:49:27,167
And, you know, generally, what are the implications going forward?

559
00:49:27,207 --> 00:49:29,369
I just wanted to understand that from you.

560
00:49:30,439 --> 00:49:32,280
Good evening, Jack Buckley, Chief of Police.

561
00:49:33,540 --> 00:49:35,000
So the question is how do we arrive at it?

562
00:49:35,020 --> 00:49:41,542
So it came about through the collective bargaining process with the Superior Officers Union and the city and the mayor's office.

563
00:49:42,302 --> 00:49:57,127
And I think it's something that the city has been planning to kind of change the future of the police department over the last, I've been in the office now eight years and there's been a lot of work being done to professionalize the police department from where it was.

564
00:49:57,187 --> 00:49:58,327
Like every leader should,

565
00:49:59,216 --> 00:50:02,617
work to grow their organization, and this is part of that next step.

566
00:50:03,277 --> 00:50:12,761
Since it is a civil service position, and it does impact the future of the members of the Superior Officers Union, it becomes a collective bargaining agreement, right?

567
00:50:12,801 --> 00:50:14,681
So they would have to negotiate over those impacts.

568
00:50:15,162 --> 00:50:20,964
And so the city did that with the unions, and the unions did agree to go forward.

569
00:50:20,984 --> 00:50:25,225
And so that's why it became part of the collective bargaining agreement and settled in there.

570
00:50:25,865 --> 00:50:27,666
The benefits of it, I mean,

571
00:50:29,026 --> 00:50:31,767
I think a catalyst, let me go back a little bit.

572
00:50:31,807 --> 00:50:35,769
One of the catalysts is that there was a recent change of civil service law in 2025.

573
00:50:36,429 --> 00:50:42,332
So the best way I could kind of explain this is in 2018, we had three captains.

574
00:50:42,952 --> 00:50:45,113
Civil service law stated that an auto,

575
00:50:45,913 --> 00:50:53,394
to have a test for the next chief of police, you have to have four individuals in the grade below chief of police eligible to take that test.

576
00:50:53,954 --> 00:50:56,215
So they didn't have it, and it opened up to lieutenants.

577
00:50:56,755 --> 00:51:01,476
So instead of having three candidates eligible and competing for the job, they had an additional nine.

578
00:51:01,696 --> 00:51:02,156
So that was 12.

579
00:51:03,076 --> 00:51:09,877
It allowed me to compete for the job, and I ended up being a successful candidate, so I think it was the right process.

580
00:51:10,957 --> 00:51:14,078
But now, with the change of civil service law, the law only is two.

581
00:51:15,027 --> 00:51:21,869
And at any given time, you know, a captain, you've got to imagine, is a senior officer, right?

582
00:51:21,889 --> 00:51:23,469
They've been around for many, many years.

583
00:51:23,549 --> 00:51:28,911
And at any given time, if you only have two qualified candidates, you restrict the amount internally in-house, how many you could have.

584
00:51:29,051 --> 00:51:31,532
And it excludes, like, my lieutenants.

585
00:51:31,592 --> 00:51:36,053
And a lot of lieutenants do a lot of good work and are qualified to sort of compete for that job.

586
00:51:36,713 --> 00:51:41,755
So internally, that was one of the driving points that was restricting a lot of internal offices from competing.

587
00:51:42,176 --> 00:51:48,879
But externally, I think professionally, we know that you want to open this job up to the best candidate you could possibly find.

588
00:51:48,959 --> 00:51:53,121
This is not getting, this job is not getting easier, it's getting tougher, right?

589
00:51:53,181 --> 00:51:59,524
And you want to find somebody with qualified and there's some experience that could come in here and bring, sometimes bring new ideas.

590
00:51:59,984 --> 00:52:02,165
It's not always the case, but if you have that option,

591
00:52:02,565 --> 00:52:03,546
It's why you should look at it.

592
00:52:04,187 --> 00:52:09,831
And most police departments in cities, right, larger police departments do this and work in that manner.

593
00:52:09,931 --> 00:52:11,332
So hopefully that answered the question.

594
00:52:11,713 --> 00:52:13,514
Yeah, it's a good helpful answer.

595
00:52:13,574 --> 00:52:17,537
And my only other question, this mentions deputy chief.

596
00:52:18,298 --> 00:52:18,438
Yes.

597
00:52:18,498 --> 00:52:18,839
Is that a?

598
00:52:20,208 --> 00:52:21,028
It would be a new position.

599
00:52:21,048 --> 00:52:22,369
We do not have a deputy position.

600
00:52:23,250 --> 00:52:25,951
So a deputy chief would fall right under the rank of chief of police.

601
00:52:26,171 --> 00:52:32,895
So currently, as chief of police with three captains, this would be chief of police, deputy chief, and three captains, should they fill it.

602
00:52:32,915 --> 00:52:35,436
There's no guarantee that the city ultimately will fill it.

603
00:52:35,596 --> 00:52:38,558
But as I said, this job is getting tougher.

604
00:52:38,778 --> 00:52:44,861
And I'm not getting younger, but as a lot of you know, I got sick this past year.

605
00:52:47,503 --> 00:52:51,066
It's always beneficial to have somebody who's ready to step into that executive role.

606
00:52:51,586 --> 00:52:55,030
And you have three captains, and they're all busy doing a lot of other things.

607
00:52:55,070 --> 00:53:05,299
And if you can have somebody step in, and so from my learning experience, having a deputy chief who kind of can take my place in a lot of different instances, then it's beneficial for the police department.

608
00:53:05,340 --> 00:53:06,801
That's why a lot of departments do that.

609
00:53:07,602 --> 00:53:07,722
Yeah.

610
00:53:08,062 --> 00:53:09,944
I liked that we were doing kind of a triumvirate

611
00:53:10,600 --> 00:53:15,181
you know, Roman Republic style approach there to fill in for you, but no.

612
00:53:15,562 --> 00:53:30,566
I just want to understand because I was like, I don't know that position now and I wasn't sure if that was a quirk of the law or if that was an intent to create a new position or it's just an option to have that position outside of civil service in the future or if it was even maybe a proposal that there be two captains and a deputy chief or something like that.

613
00:53:30,586 --> 00:53:31,946
So I just wanted to understand a little bit.

614
00:53:34,407 --> 00:53:35,989
I would push strongly for a deputy chief.

615
00:53:36,049 --> 00:53:44,175
And again, it's budget issues and all this sort of stuff, because it helps, obviously, relieve some of the burden for me, because I put a lot on my three captains.

616
00:53:45,156 --> 00:53:54,364
And then for me to keep putting things on, I feel, when I left my illness, I felt guilty that I was leaving a lot into people's hands.

617
00:53:54,424 --> 00:54:00,809
And I just think it's beneficial for this police department to have that extra resource at that executive level, as I said.

618
00:54:02,822 --> 00:54:06,565
It's highly beneficial, and that's why most police departments run with the deputy chief.

619
00:54:07,065 --> 00:54:07,305
Okay.

620
00:54:08,025 --> 00:54:08,266
All right.

621
00:54:09,506 --> 00:54:10,087
